<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Communication</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
If you are not a seasoned raid leader, try to have some support around you with a core group of friends that you trust in which you can delegate out some responsibility. Make these your group leaders and key points of communication.<br>
<br>
I also like a right hand person sort of a co-leader...<br>
<br>
Raid Leader:  Leader deals with the strats, moving the group, positioning, makes the call to camp clerics, choice on MA, choice on group, expert on zone, picks key buffers, group leaders,etc.<br>
<br>
Raid Officer:  Loot distribution, arguments, coordinating on getting other classes that you need to the raid that have not shown up (clerics, enchanters usually), kicking people off the raid that get out of hand, sets up your chat room after buffing if you are planning to camp the group prior to raid, etc.<br>
<br>
Make sure YOU and the raid officer are the only people  calling the shots in /shout or it will cause confusion.  Have the group leaders be your point of contact and the  /tells that you pay attention to at the raid. Ignore all other direct tells or you will go insane.<br>
<br>
*****<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>     Less is better! </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
The less people you have the easier it is to manage.  Know the clases and levels you need and create balanced groups as much as possible. Then close them off when you have enough people.  <br>
<br>
<br>
****<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Do's &amp; Don'ts</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Do have a good CR plan in advance.<br>
<br>
Do post your rules in advance of the raid.  <br>
<br>
Don't be afraid to tell a person to leave if they do not follow directions, act like an idiot, or spam in ooc and shout.<br>
<br>
Don't be afraid to cancel a raid if the majority of people you have do not listen to directions.<br>
<br>
Don't think it's going to be easy the first time.  Try to remain cool.  You staying level headed sets the tone for the rest of your raiders.<br>
<br>
Don't expect that you own the rights to a plane or dragon just b/c you plan a pick up raid in advance or schedule it here on NT.  Those days are over as mentioned in the flame thread.  I find most guilds will not walk over you but if you are not organized, do not have the numbers, and are not ready to move, then you are shit outta luck and need to move on.  Just try again another time.  It's just how it goes unfortunatly.  People are always going to be arguing over spawns and camps.  However, 90% of the guild /raid leaders on this server I find very reasonable and will work with you.<br>
<br>
****<br>
Personally, I don't do pick-ups unless they are people that I know well ingame that are leading,  close friends,<br>
or small groups.  When I first started to attend the big dragon/plane raid pick ups I had great fun. Even the chaos, although annoying at times, was exciting.  Plus it was a great way to meet people outside of the guild.  Now I just prefer more structured gameplay.  It makes it easier to accomplish the task and decreases downtime.<br>
<br>
Good luck Pokka!  I applaud your efforts in advance!  You may want to also review previous plane/dragon raid posts for more specific rules.  Hope this helps.<br>
